8.4 — Permissioning & Audit Logs
This section defines the platform-wide control plane governing authority, state transitions, override behavior, and immutable logging.
It applies to all features listed in the Master Feature Catalog and must align with:
• Logging & Downgrade Doctrine
• QA & Regression Doctrine
• Founder Operational Control Layer (FOCL)
• Causality Model (CCO)
• Stress Testing Framework
This section is implementation-binding.
No conceptual interpretation is permitted at runtime.

8.4.1 Purpose
The Permissioning & Audit system defines:
• Who can act
• What can change
• What can never change
• How actions are logged
• How overrides expire
• How logging failure affects runtime behavior
It protects:
• Data integrity
• Governance integrity
• Regional isolation
• User trust
• Founder accountability
• 24–48 hour survivability without Founder login
The system must:
• Enforce permissions at the database layer
• Emit structured, machine-readable events for all state transitions
• Prevent silent override
• Prevent silent downgrade
• Prevent permanent override without expiry
• Prevent log mutation

